Assignment 1
Observe the structureas of a given EMPLOYEE table as below and suggest if this table can be further Normalized
EMPNO, ENAME, SAL, DEPTNO, DNAME, LOC
Explain what normal form this table is and how you can make this into next normal form

Solution-

Table: EMPLOYEE (EMPNO, ENAME, SAL, DEPTNO, DNAME, LOC)

This table is in 2NF right now. EMPNO is the primary key and all
values are atomic so 1NF is satisfied. There is no composite key
so no partial dependency either which means 2NF is also satisfied.

But it is NOT in 3NF because of a transitive dependency.
DNAME and LOC depend on DEPTNO, not directly on EMPNO.
So the dependency chain is: EMPNO -> DEPTNO -> DNAME, LOC
This violates 3NF.

To convert to 3NF we split it into two tables:

EMPLOYEE (EMPNO, ENAME, SAL, DEPTNO)
  - Primary Key: EMPNO
  - Foreign Key: DEPTNO

DEPARTMENT (DEPTNO, DNAME, LOC)
  - Primary Key: DEPTNO




Assignment 2
Observe the structureas of a given STUDENT table as below and suggest if this table can be further Normalized
ROLLNO, NAME, AGE, EXAM, MARKS, GRADE
Explain what normal form this table is and how you can make this into next normal form

Solution-

Table: STUDENT (ROLLNO, NAME, AGE, EXAM, MARKS, GRADE)

This table is in 1NF. Values are atomic but there is a problem
with partial dependency.

A student gives multiple exams so the primary key has to be
composite: (ROLLNO, EXAM)

Now:
- MARKS depends on both ROLLNO and EXAM (full dependency) - ok
- NAME and AGE depend only on ROLLNO, not on EXAM (partial dependency)
This violates 2NF.

To convert to 2NF we split it into two tables:

STUDENT_INFO (ROLLNO, NAME, AGE)
  - Primary Key: ROLLNO

STUDENT_RESULTS (ROLLNO, EXAM, MARKS, GRADE)
  - Primary Key: (ROLLNO, EXAM)
  - Foreign Key: ROLLNO


Assignment 3
Observe the structure of a given EMPLOYEE table and suggest what kind of problem this table has and how to solve the problem
EMPNO, PROJECT_NO, NO_OF_DAYS, CUSTOMERNAME
In the above table EMPNO AND PROJECT_NO both are together a composite primary key

Solution-

Table: EMPLOYEE (EMPNO, PROJECT_NO, NO_OF_DAYS, CUSTOMERNAME)
Composite Primary Key: (EMPNO, PROJECT_NO)

This table is in 1NF but violates 2NF due to partial dependency.

- NO_OF_DAYS depends on both EMPNO and PROJECT_NO (full dependency) - ok
- CUSTOMERNAME depends only on PROJECT_NO, not on EMPNO
  because the customer of a project stays the same no matter
  which employee is working on it.
This is a partial dependency which violates 2NF.

To convert to 2NF we split it into two tables:

EMPLOYEE_PROJECT (EMPNO, PROJECT_NO, NO_OF_DAYS)
  - Primary Key: (EMPNO, PROJECT_NO)
  - Foreign Key: PROJECT_NO

PROJECT (PROJECT_NO, CUSTOMERNAME)
  - Primary Key: PROJECT_NO
